;; Clay project config for the notebook sprite. Read from the JVM's working
;; directory (/home/sprite/notebook) on every `make!` call.
;;
;; `:browse :browser` suppresses Calva's "flare" — the in-editor webview Clay
;; asks Calva to open when a form is rendered with `{:ide :calva}` (the option
;; Calva Power Tools' Clay commands pass). That webview targets the sprite's
;; internal http://localhost:1971/, which the browser can't reach, so it just
;; renders a dead "Unable to connect" pane next to the editor. Clay only emits
;; the flare when `(and ide (not= browse :browser))` (clay's make.clj), so
;; `:browse :browser` turns it off. The form still renders into the running
;; Clay server — which our workspace already shows in the live output pane — so
;; nothing is lost. Clay would only actually open a browser when no live-reload
;; client is connected; our output pane always is (and the sprite is headless),
;; so nothing pops. The whole-file render in watch.clj passes an explicit
;; `:browse false` and no `:ide`, so it overrides this and is unaffected.
{:browse :browser}
